- `converter.ConvertFrom("&h2")`: *does not* throw in .NET Framework; *does not* throw in .NET Core
- `converter.ConvertFrom("&H2")`: *does not* throw in .NET Framework; *does not* throw in .NET Core

There are several bugs, both in .NET Core and in .NET Framework due to incorrect order of precedence between the && and the || operators.

The intention of the code is to disallow (throw) the following:
- `converter.ConvertFrom("#2")`
- `converter.ConvertFrom("0x2")`
- `converter.ConvertFrom("0X2")`
- `converter.ConvertFrom("&h2")`
- `converter.ConvertFrom("&H2")`

This is because all these representations above are hex, but `AllowHex` only applies to the first condition in the following list of `... || ...` due to the order of precedence. Changed bracketing would fix this

